'''Ahmad Khani''', '''Ahmad-i Khani''' ({{lang-ku|'''EhmedÃª XanÃ®'''}}, (1650 [[Hakkari]] â€“1707 [[DoÄŸubayazÄ±t]]) was a [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] [[writer]], [[poet]], [[astronomer]] and [[philosopher]].<ref>http://www.kurdishacademy.org/?q=node/81</ref> He was born amongst the Khani's tribe in [[Hakkari]] province in present-day [[Turkey]]. He moved to Bayezid in Ritkan province and settled there. Later he started with teaching [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] ([[Kurmanji]]) at basic level. Khani was fluent in Kurdish, [[Arabic]] and [[Persian language|Persian]]. He wrote his Arabic-Kurdish dictionary "NÃ»bihara BiÃ§Ã»kan" (The Spring of Children) in 1683 to help children with their learning process.<ref>http://www.ehmedexani.org {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150801100448/http://ehmedexani.org/ |date=1 August 2015 }}</ref>
His most important work is the Kurdish classic love story "[[Mem and Zin]]" (Mem Ã» ZÃ®n) (1692).<ref>[http://www.institutkurde.org/en/language www.institutkurde.org]</ref>
His other work include a book called ''EqÃ®deya ÃmanÃª'' (The Path of Faith), which is part poem and part [[prose]]. The book explains the five pillars of Islamic faith. It was published in 2000 in Sweden.
