{{Infobox Jewish leader | honorific-prefix = | name = Elazar ben Moshe Azikri | honorific-suffix = | title = | image = ×¨×‘×™ ××œ×¢×–×¨ ××–×›×¨×™.JPG | caption = Rabbi Elazar Azikri's grave in [[Safed]] | synagogue = | synagogueposition = | yeshiva = | yeshivaposition = | organisation = | organisationposition = | began = | ended = | predecessor = | successor = | rabbi = | rebbe = | kohan = | hazzan = | rank = | other_post = <!---------- Personal details ----------> | birth_name = | birth_date = 1533 | birth_place = [[Safed]], [[Ottoman Empire]] | death_date = 1600 | death_place = [[Safed]], [[Ottoman Empire]] | yahrtzeit = | buried = | nationality = | denomination = | residence = | dynasty = | parents = | father = | mother = | spouse = | children = | occupation = | profession = | alma_mater = | semicha = | signature = }}
Rabbi '''Elazar ben Moshe Azikri''' ({{lang-he|××œ×¢×–×¨ ×‘×Ÿ ××©×” ××–×›×¨×™&lrm;}}) (1533â€“1600) was a Jewish [[kabbalist]], [[poet]] and [[writer]], born in [[Safed]] to a [[Sephardic]] family who had settled in the [[Land of Israel]] after the expulsion from [[Spain]].
[[Rabbi]] Elazar studied [[Torah]] under [[Rabbi]] Yosef Sagis and Rabbi [[Jacob Berab]], and is counted with the greatest Rabbis and intellectuals of his time: [[Shlomo Halevi Alkabetz]], [[Yosef Karo]], [[Moshe Cordovero]], [[Isaac Luria]], [[Israel Najara]], etc.
In 1588 Rabbi Elazar founded the "Sukat Shalom" movement who acted to arouse in Jews the devotion to religion.
Rabbi Elazar died in 1600 and was buried in Safed.
==Works== Rabbi Elazar's Book, the ''Sefer Haredim'' (×¡×¤×¨ ×—×¨×“×™×), printed after his death in 1600, is considered as one of the main books of Jewish [[deontology]].
He also wrote a commentary on ''Tractate Bezah''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jtsa.edu/progs/tal/isfrancus/index.shtml |title=Dr. Israel Francus |accessdate=2007-08-26 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040413041508/http://www.jtsa.edu/progs/tal/isfrancus/index.shtml |archivedate=April 13, 2004 |df= }}</ref> and Berachot<ref>Printed in the Vilna Yerushalmi Brachot.</ref> of the [[Jerusalem Talmud]].
The ''[[Piyyut]]'' (liturgical poem) ''[[Yedid Nefesh]]'' (×™×“×™×“ × ×¤×©) is commonly attributed to Rabbi Elazar, who first published it in his Sefer Haredim. Recent findings, however, have raised the possibility that ''[[Yedid Nefesh]]'' actually predates Rabbi Elazar by about a century, leaving the true authorship a mystery.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Reif |first1=Stefan C. |title=The Hebrew Manuscripts at Cambridge University Libraries |date=1997 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=9780521583398 |page=93 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Hebrew_Manuscripts_at_Cambridge_Universi.html?id=MDuYkcahsq8C&printsec=frontcover&source=kp_read_button#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>
