{{Infobox writer | name = Friedrich Wagenfeld | image = | imagesize = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_date = 3 January 1810 | birth_place = Bremen | death_date = 26 August 1846 | death_place = Bremen | occupation = | nationality = German | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | debut_works = | influences = | influenced = | signature = | website = | footnotes = }} '''Friedrich Wagenfeld''' (January 3, 1810 &ndash; August 26, 1846) was a German [[philologist]] and author born in [[Bremen]].
==Life== Wegenfeld was born in Bremen in 1810.<ref name=ws>[https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=de&u=http://de.wikisource.org/wiki/ADB:Wagenfeld,_Friedrich&ei=wZqkSffEE4yPngew5PyXBQ&sa=X&oi=translate&resnum=5&ct=result&prev=/search%3Fq%3D%2522Bremer%2BVolkssagen%2522%2BWagenfeld%26hl%3Den%26sa%3DG Wikisource] translated biography @ [[Allgemeine Deutsche Biographie]]</ref>
From 1829 to 1832 Wegenfeld studied [[philology]] in [[GÃ¶ttingen]], and subsequently spent several years serving as a tutor in [[Brinkum]]. He lived and worked as a writer in Bremen, where he died on August 26, 1846 at the age of 36.<ref name=ws/>
Wagenfeld was the author a popular collection of Bremen [[Folklore|folk tales]] titled ''Bremer Volkssagen'' (1844â€“45). In 1837 he published what purportedly was the entire text of [[Philo of Byblos]]' ''[[Sanchoniathon]]'', allegedly found in the Portuguese convent of Santa Maria de MerinhÃ£o. This publication, however, was soon afterwards proven by several scholars to be a fabrication.<ref name=farrer>{{cite book|last=Farrer|first=James Anson|title=Literary Forgeries|date=1969|isbn=1435750985|page=191 on|url=https://books.google.com/books?isbn=1435750985|display-authors=etal}}</ref>
Today there is a street named Lazy Street and the [[House of the Seven Lazy Brothers]] in Bremen which celebrate Wagenfeld's work and in particular his story of the Seven Lazy brothers.<ref>[http://www.bremen-tourism.de/bremen-legends Bremen legends], Bremen tourism, retrieved 5 February 2014</ref>
