{{One source|date=May 2009}}

The only official language of the [[Falkland Islands]] is [[English language|English]], and this is spoken by almost everyone on a day-to-day basis. [[Spanish language|Spanish]] is spoken by 10% of the population<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fig.gov.fk/policy/index.php/component/jdownloads/finish/5-statistics/4789-falkland-islands-census-2016-report-without-data-tables/0?Itemid=0#page=31|title=2016 Census Report|last=|first=|date=|year=2017|website=|publisher=Policy and Economic Development Unit, Falkland Islands Government|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180124213315/http://www.fig.gov.fk/policy/index.php/component/jdownloads/finish/5-statistics/4789-falkland-islands-census-2016-report-without-data-tables/0?Itemid=0|archive-date=2018-01-24|dead-url=|access-date=}}</ref>, a significant minority. Most of the Spanish speakers are immigrants, foreign workers, and expats, predominantly from [[Chilean people|Chile]] and [[Argentine people|Argentina]].

==Falkland English dialect==
{{main|Falkland Islands English}}
[[Falkland Islands]] [[English language|English]] is mainly [[British English|British]] in character.  However, as a result of the isolation of the islands, the small population has developed and retains its own accent/dialect, which persists despite a large number of immigrants from the [[United Kingdom]] in recent years. In rural areas (i.e. anywhere outside [[Port Stanley]]), known as  â€˜[[Camp (Falkland Islands)|Camp]]â€™ (from [[Spanish language|Spanish]] ''campo'' or â€˜countrysideâ€™),<ref>[http://www.falklandislands.com/section.php/80/1/camping  Stay with us Â» Camping:  Falkland Islands Tourist Board]</ref> the Falkland accent tends to be stronger. The dialect has resemblances to [[Australian English|Australian]], [[New Zealand English|New Zealand]], [[West Country dialects|West Country]] and [[Norfolk dialect]]s of English, as well as [[Scots (language)|Lowland Scots]].

==Historic==
Several languages have been used historically in the Falkland Islands.

* [[French language|French]] â€“ the French were the first to colonise the islands, and their settlement at [[Port Louis, Falkland Islands|Port Louis]] would have used French. The islands' French name, Iles Malouines, stems from [[Saint-Malo]].
* [[Yaghan language|Yaghan]] â€“ a missionary settlement on [[Keppel Island]] contained many [[Yaghan]]s from [[Tierra del Fuego]]. The [[Falkland Islands fox]] was previously hypothesized to represent a possible pre-European landing on the Falklands, but this has since been refuted.<ref name="Httpwwwsciencedailycomreleaseshtm">{{cite web | url = https://www.sciencedaily.com/releases/2009/11/091102121449.htm | title = New Clues To Extinct Falklands Wolf Mystery | accessdate = 2011-09-03 | date = 2009-11-03 | work = EurekAlert | publisher = Science Daily}}</ref> This language has left no trace on the Falklands, and would not have been written at this time.<ref>Bridges, E L (1948) ''The Uttermost Part of the Earth'' Republished 2008, Overlook Press {{ISBN|978-1-58567-956-0}}</ref>
* [[Scottish Gaelic]] â€“ many early settlers were from the Gaelic-speaking parts of Scotland, including the [[Western Isles]] and the western [[Scottish Highlands|Highlands]]. William Blain, a settler from [[Dumfries]], noted in 1878 that "the Scotch language was fairly well represented" and a majority of the population were "Scotch or of Scotch descendants".<ref>David Britain and Andrea Sudbury, "Falkland Islands English", in ''The Lesser-Known Varieties of English: An Introduction" (eds. Daniel Schreier, Peter Trudgill, Edgar W. Schneider, Jeffrey P. Williams), Cambridge University Press, 2010, p. 213.</ref>

