{{Infobox language family |name=Tequistlatecan |altname=''Chontal de Oaxaca'' |region=[[Oaxaca]] |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Hokan languages|Hokan]] ? |glotto=tequ1244 |glottorefname=Tequistlatecan |child1=Highland Chontal |child2=Coastal Chontal |map= Tolatecan Languages.png |mapcaption= The Tequistlatecan languages are in Mexico at the left of the map. }}
The '''Tequistlatecan languages''', also called '''Chontal of Oaxaca''', are three close but distinct languages spoken or once spoken by the [[Oaxaca Chontal people|Chontal people]] of [[Oaxaca]] State, Mexico.
They were spoken by 4,400 people in 2010.{{#tag:ref|[[INALI]] (2012) [http://site.inali.gob.mx/pdf/libro_lenguas_indigenas_nacionales_en_riesgo_de_desaparicion.pdf ''MÃ©xico: Lenguas indÃ­genas nacionales]''|name=INALI}}
==Languages== *[[Huamelultec language|Huamelultec]] (Lowland Oaxaca Chontal), *[[Tequistlatec language|Tequistlatec]] (extinct), *[[Highland Oaxaca Chontal]].
==Name== Although most authors use the form ''tequistlatec(an)'' today, this is based on an improper derivation in Nahuatl (the correct derivation from ''TequisistlÃ¡n'' would be ''Tequisistec(an)'', and both terms were used by [[Edward Sapir|Sapir]] interchangeably).
==Classification== The Tequistlatecan languages are part the proposed [[Hokan languages|Hokan]] family, but are often considered to be distinct family. Campbell and Oltrogge (1980) proposed that the Tequistlatecan languages may be related to [[Jicaquean languages|Jicaquean]] (see [[Tolatecan languages|Tolatecan]]), but this hypothesis has not been generally accepted.
